Simon Antwi and Steven Durtka

2024-12-5

Topic

The impact of immigration on housing prices in the US

Motivation

Immigration entails the movement of people from one country to another to settle there permanently or temporarily. However, in our context, we will also be taking into consideration intra-immigration (within the country). Numerous factors, such as economic opportunities, escaping conflict or persecution, reuniting with family, or for educational purposes, inform immigration decisions for person moving between nations. Family, employment, educational pursuits, or other interests are some underlying reasons people may choose to relocate within the U.S. Housing prices stand for the cost of purchasing properties, such as houses, apartments, or condominiums. Immigration significantly impacts all facets of the US economy, including the housing market. We want to investigate the impact of immigrants influx (both domestic and foreign) on local housing prices, considering also the demand and supply factors in the market such as interest rates and general population increases. Why it Matters. To begin with, it is crucial for policymakers as it assists them in making informed decisions regarding immigration, with which they can help steady the housing prices to ensure affordability and a high standard of living. Furthermore, it can facilitate the establishment of a stable market, as both homeowners and renters have a reasonable insight into the fluctuations in the housing market. Lastly, it can also serve as a guide for urban planning and infrastructure planning and development.

Research Questions

  1. What is the relationship between migration and housing prices. (Descriptive, Predictive)

  2. The distribution patterns of migration and housing prices across states and time. (Descriptive)

  3. The impact of urbanization driven by migration on housing prices. (Descriptive)

  4. How does the effect on housing prices vary according to counties? (Descriptive)

Data Description

Migration Data Sets

(https://www.irs.gov/statistics/soi-tax-stats-migration-data-2013-2020) The data was sourced from the Internal Revenue Service (IRS). The migration is data based on year-to-year address changes reported on individual income tax returns filed with the IRS. We use county-level data from 2013 to 2020. The migration data consists of both inflows and outflows people within and outside the country. N1 is the number of returns filed, approximating the number of migrated households. N2: number of personal exemptions claimed. Which approximates the number of individuals. Agi is the aggregate migration flows at the state level, which are determined by the size of adjusted gross income (AGI) and the age of the primary taxpayer. It is reported in thousands of dollars.

Housing Prices Data Set

(https://www.fhfa.gov/sites/default/files/2024-09/UADAggs_county_v3_2.zip) The Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA) provided the housing price data set. We used the uniform appraisal datasetaggregate statistics on appraisalfrom the FHFA. An appraisal is an assessment of a propertys value performed by a certified appraiser. It is quarterly data. The data spans from 2021- to 2022-year period. Value is the worth of the statistical series. Quarter 1 = January March 2 = April-June 3 = July-September. 4 = October-December 5 = all four quarters (yearly) NB: For this research purpose we are using 5 which represent annual housing value. Geoname is the formal name of a geographic unit (counties).

Prime Interest Rates

The control variable is interest rate from 2013 to 2020. The interest rates were scraped from the JP Morgan Bank website and averaged by year.

How Migration data and Housing data are related.

There is a close relationship between migration data and the housing data set. Migration patterns can directly influence the demand for housing. Areas facing elevated levels of immigration may see increased development to meet demand. This can affect housing prices depending on how fast supply can catch up.

The two data sets were merged by year and the state and county FIPS code.

Data Processing

Migration Data

There were no missing values. Column names were changed to be more descriptive. Only county level in-flow data was kept in the data set. Each year has its own file.

Because the migration data is based on tax return filings, it may under represent the actual migration into the county because there may be some people move in and out that do not file a tax return.

Housing Prices Data

We had no missing values, however some housing prices were suppressed by the Federal Housing Finance Agency if there were less than five values for a county. However, we used all data in the data set for housing values from purchase prices and not refinance appraisals since our focus is on the housing market. Only data for the fifty states and the District of Columbia were included in the final data set.

Housing price data was subset by year, and each year joined to the corresponding migration data using the state and county FIPS codes as keys. All the years were bound into one data frame for analysis, and the average prime interest rate for each year was added as a separate column.

Both migration data and housing price data were log transformed due to their distributions being skewed.

Exploratory Analysis

Finding 1: The relationship between migration and housing prices

There is a clear positive non-linear relationship (upward sloping pattern) between number of individuals inflow (migrants) and housing prices. This indicates as the number of migrants increases, housing prices also tends to increase. The points are tightly clustered around a linear trend suggesting a high correlation.

There is an overall positive relationship between immigration and housing prices, as indicated by the upward trend. As the NO_OF_INDIVIDUALS(INFLOW) increases, VALUE also tends to increase, suggesting a direct association(correlation) between these two variables. This also affirms the relationship between the variables by the scatter graph even though this show a non - linear relationship

The CEF shows a clear linear upward sloping trend(positive relationship between migrations and housing prices). This suggests that higher levels of migrations are generally associated with higher house value.

Polynomial Regression

Predicting the fitted values This graph shows a scatter plot of the relationship between Number of Immigrants (on the x-axis) and Housing Prices (on the y-axis), with a fourth-order polynomial regression line (in orange) fitted to the data. The graph show an overall positive trend between the two variables, where housing prices increase as the number of immigrants grows, but with considerable spread. The polynomial regression captures all the complexities that would have otherwise be smoothen out by fitting a linear regression. At the initial stages the housing prices increase as the number of immigrants rises. The curve begins to flatten at the middle part (showing slow rate of increase in housing prices) and peaks again. And at the tail end has a slight downward slope indicating that increase in immigrant no longer had an impact on housing prices.

Bin Regression

The scatter plot provides a clear relationship between the housing prices and migration. The dense cloud of points indicates a positive correlation between migration and housing prices. As migration increases, housing prices also tends to increase, showing a general upward trend.

Cubic Splines This plot shows the relationship between the number of immigrants and housing prices, with a fitted regression line using cubic splines with 5 degrees of freedom. The spline curve shows a non-linear positive relationship between the number of immigrants and housing prices. At lower levels of immigration, housing prices rise gradually. As the number of immigrants increases, the slope of the curve becomes steeper, indicating a faster rate of increase in housing prices.This could suggest that states with higher numbers of immigrants experience higher demand for housing, leading to increased housing prices.
